36 vs. [[Minnesota State University, Mankato|Mankato State]]<br>'''W''' 7\u20135 vs. New Haven<br>'''W''' 9\u20131 vs. [[Sacramento State University|Sacramento State]]<br>'''W''' 5\u20130 vs. [[Columbus State University|Columbus College]]\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\"\n| 1987 || 4\u20130 || '''College World Series''' || '''W''' 6\u20130 vs. [[University of Tampa|Tampa]]<br>'''W''' 6\u20132 vs. [[California State University, Dominguez Hills|Cal State-Dominguez Hills]]<br>'''W''' 8\u20137 vs. Wright State<br>'''W''' 7\u20135 vs. Tampa\n|- style=\"text-align:left;\"\n| 1993 || 2\u20132 || '''College World Series''' || '''W''' 5\u20130 vs. [[Mansfield University of Pennsylvania|Pennsylvania-Mansfield]]<br>'''L''' 1\u201313 vs. Tampa<br>'''W''' 7\u20132 vs. Pennsylvania-Mansfield<br>'''L''' 3\u20134 vs. Tampa\n|-  class=\"unsortable\" style=\"text-align:center; background:#8e0028;\"\n|| <span style=\"color:silver;\">'''Totals'''</span>\n|| <span style=\"color:silver;\">'''14\u201310'''</span>\n|| <span style=\"color:silver;\">'''7 Appearances'''</span>\n|| <span style=\"color:silver;\"> </span>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of NCAA Division I baseball programs]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website}}\n\n{{Troy Trojans baseball navbox}}\n{{Sun Belt Conference baseball navbox}}\n{{Troy University}}\n\n[[Category:Troy Trojans baseball| ]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Troy_Trojans_baseball"}
{"title_page": "Never Without You", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Never Without You\n| cover      = Never Without You cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Ringo Starr]]\n| album      = [[Ringo Rama]]\n| B-side     = Instant Amnesia\n| released   = 3 March 2003\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2002\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 4:15 (Radio Edit)<br/>5:24 (album version)\n| label      = [[Koch Records|Koch]]\n| writer     = Ringo Starr, [[Mark Hudson (musician)|Mark Hudson]], [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Hudson (musician)|Mark Hudson]]\n| prev_title = La De Da\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Liverpool 8 (song)|Liverpool 8]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n\"'''Never Without You'''\" is a [[The Beatles Tributes|tribute]] song from [[Ringo Starr]] to his former [[Beatles]] bandmate [[George Harrison]] who died on 29 November 2001.  The recording appeared on Starr's 2003 album ''[[Ringo Rama]]'', and was also released as a single.\n\n==History==\n\"Never Without You\" was co-written by Starr, [[Mark Hudson (musician)|Mark Hudson]] and [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]].  Starr commented: \"Gary Nicholson started that song, and Mark brought it over and we realized we could tailor it. George was really on my mind then.\" In a 2003 interview, Starr said that he had remained closest to Harrison of all the former Beatles following the group's break-up in 1970, and that the song conveyed \"how I miss him in my heart and in music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/r-i-n-g-o |title=R-I-N-G-O|last=Ruttenberg |first=Jay|date=24 July 2003|work=[[Time Out New York]]|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe recording includes a lead guitar part by Harrison's friend [[Eric Clapton]]. Starr said of Clapton's contribution: \"Eric's on two tracks on the album [''Ringo Rama''], but I really wanted him on this song because George loved Eric and Eric loved George.\" Clapton uses Harrison's favourite technique, the [[slide guitar]], to achieve the characteristic sound of a song of the deceased former Beatle.\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe heartfelt lyrics of \"Never Without You\" are sometimes misquoted<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://songmeanings.com/songs/view/3530822107858543305/|title=Ringo Starr - Never Without You Lyrics|website=SongMeanings}}</ref>, especially the following lines, which refer to the titles of two of Harrison's songs from the Beatles' ''[[Abbey Road]]'' and Harrison's ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' albums respectively:\n* \"[[Here Comes the Sun]]\" is about you\n* \"[[I Dig Love]]\" is about you\n\nStarr uses the [[riff]]-driven melody from Harrison's song \"[[What Is Life]]\" in the middle of \"Never Without You\", right before he makes reference to \"[[All Things Must Pass (song)|All Things Must Pass]]\". The lyrics also mention Harrison's composition \"[[Within You Without You]]\" from the Beatles' ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' album. After the first chorus, the lyric goes \u201cHere today, not alone\u201d which is a reference to the 1982 [[Paul McCartney]] song, \u201c[[Here Today (Paul McCartney song)|Here Today]]\u201d which was written as a tribute to former bandmate [[John Lennon]] after he was assassinated.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9PjnOdHq-T8 Music Video of \"Never Without You\"]\n*Misquoted {{MetroLyrics song|ringo-starr|never-without-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Ringo Starr}}\n\n[[Category:Ringo Starr songs]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ringo Starr]]\n[[Category:Songs in memory of deceased persons]]\n[[Category:Songs inspired by deaths]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mark Hudson (musician)]]\n[[Category:Music published by Startling Music]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gary Nicholson]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Never Without You\n| cover      = Never Without You cover.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Ringo Starr]]\n| album      = [[Ringo Rama]]\n| B-side     = Instant Amnesia\n| released   = 3 March 2003\n| format     = [[CD single]]\n| recorded   = 2002\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| length     = 4:15 (Radio Edit)<br/>5:24 (album version)\n| label      = [[Koch Records|Koch]]\n| writer     = Ringo Starr, [[Mark Hudson (musician)|Mark Hudson]], [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]]\n| producer   = [[Mark Hudson (musician)|Mark Hudson]]\n| prev_title = La De Da\n| prev_year  = 1998\n| next_title = [[Liverpool 8 (song)|Liverpool 8]]\n| next_year  = 2007\n}}\n\"'''Never Without You'''\" is a [[The Beatles Tributes|tribute]] song from [[Ringo Starr]] to his former [[Beatles]] bandmate [[George Harrison]] who died on 29 November 2001.  The recording appeared on Starr's 2003 album ''[[Ringo Rama]]'', and was also released as a single.\n\n==History==\n\"Never Without You\" was co-written by Starr, [[Mark Hudson (musician)|Mark Hudson]] and [[Gary Nicholson (singer)|Gary Nicholson]].  Starr commented: \"Gary Nicholson started that song, and Mark brought it over and we realized we could tailor it. George was really on my mind then.\" In a 2003 interview, Starr said that he had remained closest to Harrison of all the former Beatles following the group's break-up in 1970, and that the song conveyed \"how I miss him in my heart and in music\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeout.com/newyork/music/r-i-n-g-o |title=R-I-N-G-O|last=Ruttenberg |first=Jay|date=24 July 2003|work=[[Time Out New York]]|accessdate=12 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe recording includes a lead guitar part by Harrison's friend [[Eric Clapton]]. Starr said of Clapton's contribution: \"Eric's on two tracks on the album [''Ringo Rama''], but I really wanted him on this song because George loved Eric and Eric loved George.\" Clapton uses Harrison's favourite technique, the [[slide guitar]], to achieve the characteristic sound of a song of the deceased former Beatle.\n\n==Lyrics==\nThe heartfelt lyrics of \"Never Without You\" are sometimes misquoted<ref>https://songmeanings.com/songs/view/3530822107858543305/</ref>, especially the following lines, which refer to the titles of two of Harrison's songs from the Beatles' ''[[Abbey Road]]'' and Harrison's ''[[All Things Must Pass]]'' albums respectively:\n* \"[[Here Comes the Sun]]\" is about you\n* \"[[I Dig Love]]\" is about you\n\nStarr uses the [[riff]]-driven melody from Harrison's song \"[[What Is Life]]\" in the middle of \"Never Without You\", right before he makes reference to \"[[All Things Must Pass (song)|All Things Must Pass]]\". The lyrics also mention Harrison's composition \"[[Within You Without You]]\" from the Beatles' ''[[Sgt. Pepper's Lonely Hearts Club Band]]'' album. After the first chorus, the lyric goes \u201cHere today, not alone\u201d which is a reference to the 1982 [[Paul McCartney]] song, \u201c[[Here Today (Paul McCartney song)|Here Today]]\u201d which was written as a tribute to former bandmate [[John Lennon]] after he was assassinated.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9PjnOdHq-T8 Music Video of \"Never Without You\"]\n*Misquoted {{MetroLyrics song|ringo-starr|never-without-you}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{Ringo Starr}}\n\n[[Category:Ringo Starr songs]]\n[[Category:2003 singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Ringo Starr]]\n[[Category:Songs in memory of deceased persons]]\n[[Category:Songs inspired by deaths]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Mark Hudson (musician)]]\n[[Category:Music published by Startling Music]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Gary Nicholson]]\n", "name_user": "Hogyn Lleol", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Never_Without_You"}
{"title_page": "World Ski and Snowboard Festival", "text_new": "[[File:WSSF FilePhoto2.jpg|alt=|thumb|WSSF File Photo]]\n[[File:WSSF File Photo3.jpg|thumb|World Ski and Snowboard Festival iTunes Concert Series]]\nThe '''World Ski & Snowboard Festival''' (WSSF) is an annual celebration of snowsports, music, arts and mountain culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=WSSF Official Website Media Page}}</ref> The Festival is held each April in [[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler, British Columbia, Canada]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Whistler,+BC/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x54873cb203957b87:0x4ab741e875f5cff6?ved=2ahUKEwi0nOOk_5rfAhWohFQKHRjnAtEQ8gEwAHoECAAQAQ|title=Whistler|website=Whistler|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> and has been recognized as the largest annual winter sports and music festival in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> It has been called the snowsport industry's version of Burning Man.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wssf.com/urlRewrite.cfm?q=wssf-facts-stats|title=Article: Ski Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe World Ski & Snowboard Festival was created by [http://www.dougperry.ca Doug Perry] in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> The festival was developed in a partnership between Perry, Tourism Whistler and Whistler/Blackcomb. \n\nThe inaugural WSSF in 1996 consisted of 22 sports events and competitions. In subsequent years it underwent exponential growth in attendance and media coverage,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/last-of-the-perry-brothers/Content?oid=2154331&storyPage=2|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine}}</ref> resulting in Whistler becoming the busiest mountain resort in North America in the month of April. At its peak, annual attendance reached an estimated 250,000 resort visits<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.news.gov.bc.ca/releases/news_releases_2013-2017/2015jtst0045-000433.pdf|title=Gov.BC.ca News Archives}}</ref>and was televised in 122 countries.\n\nAn Economic Impact Assessment<ref>Canadian Sport Tourism Alliance</ref> conducted during the 2006 event found that the WSSF generated $37.7 million in economic activity for the province of British Columbia, with visitor spending and operational expenditure injecting more than $15.7 million into the Whistler economy. Over 28,000 hotel room nights were sold during the Festival, with 86% being directly attributed to WSSF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wssf.com/urlRewrite.cfm?q=wssf-facts-stats|title=Canadian Sport Tourism Alliance}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the ownership of the festival was consolidated in a joint acquisition of Perry's ownership stake by [https://www.whistler.com Tourism Whistler] and [https://www.whistlerblackcomb.com Whistler/Blackcomb].\n\nThe predecessor to WSSF was the World Technical Skiing Championships (WTSC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> WTSC was created by [https://sites.google.com/d/1YBUBujka_cRbJd84ygLb7It7lRDBhZs2/p/14I-0LUxNreYAa5CbCfPiUVT4twC8NIwv/edit Doug Perry] as the world's first international freeskiing competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/we-are-whistler/Content?oid=2644306|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine \"20 years of WSSF\"}}</ref> The first event was staged on Blackcomb Mountain in April 1994 and was televised on ESPN in the United States and its international affiliates. WTSC was designed as a made-for-tv invitational event in which world champions, Olympians and skiing legends from the sport's major disciplines vied for the title of ''world's best all-mountain skier'' in a decathlon-format competition of freeskiing, GS racing, moguls and steeps down the Saudan Couloir. WTSC was modelled after Japan's largest skiing event, the All Japan Technical Skiing Championships, in which [http://www.dougperry.ca/photo1 Perry competed as a member of Team Salomon].\n\nThe inaugural World Technical Skiing Championships was groundbreaking in that it drew over 100 media outlets<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/festival-feedback/Content?oid=2140533|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine}}</ref> to Whistler at a time when the resort was just beginning to emerge as an international destination. The media attention seeded the idea of developing a more diverse annual event with the potential to attract more top athletes, media and attendees to Whistler Resort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/festival-feedback/Content?oid=2140533|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine}}</ref>\n\nThe 1996 World Ski & Snowboard Festival included the 2nd World Technical Skiing Championships, World Masters Alpine Open, Westbeach Snowboard Classic, Whistler Cup, Couloir Extreme Race and a ski industry symposium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> Subsequent festivals expanded to include the Whistler Concert Series, World Skiing Invitational, World Snowboarding Invitational, World Snowboarding Championship, Kokanee Boardercross, Salomon Skiercross, Pro Photographer Showdown, Filmmaker Showdown, Brave Art, State of the Art, Fashion Exposed, Multiplicity, Intersection and many others.\n\nThe World Ski & Snowboard Festival has included Canada's largest free outdoor concert series<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.topeventscanada.com/BC-top-events-festivals-TELUS-World-Ski-Snowboard-Festival.html|title=Top Events Canada}}</ref> with 50 live acts per festival. Acts on the WSSF stage have included The Black Eyed Peas, Justin Timberlake, Nickelback, Michael Franti, Nas, Toots and the Maytals, and others.\n\nFrom 2001 through 2006, the World Ski & Snowboard was televised as a four-part series on the Global Television Network and was syndicated to 122 countries.\n\nIn 2018, the World Ski & Snowboard Festival was acquired in full by Vail Resorts, Inc. upon its acquisition of Whistler Blackcomb. Vail Resorts announced WSSF would continue under new management, Crankworx Events Inc., in a shorter 6-day format, running April 10\u201315, 2018. Tourism Whistler relinquished its 22-year part ownership of the property. 2018 also marked the return of the Saudan Couloir Ski Race Extreme after a 20-year hiatus.<ref>Vancouver Courier</ref> In 2019, Vail Resorts, owner of Whistler Blackcomb, announced the World Ski & Snowboard Festival would be shortened to 5 days, running April 10-14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/world-ski-and-snowboard-festival-founder-critical-of-new-direction-of-event/Content?oid=12456969|title=World Ski and Snowboard Festival founder critical of new direction of event|last=Barrett|first=Brandon|website=Pique|language=en|access-date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the World Ski & Snowboard was acquired in full by [https://gibbonswhistler.com Gibbons Whistler] from Whistler Blackcomb.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/gibbons-whistler-buys-world-ski-and-snowboard-festival/Content?oid=14711060|title=Whistler Gibbons buys WSSF|last=|first=|date=|work=Pique Newsmagazine|access-date=}}</ref>The 2020 Festival was cancelled due to COVID-19 and the 25th Anniversary festival is scheduled for 2021.\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wssf.com World Ski and Snowboard Festival]\n\n[[Category:Snowboarding]]\n[[Category:Annual events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Whistler, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Canada]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Art festivals in Canada]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:WSSF FilePhoto2.jpg|alt=|thumb|WSSF File Photo]]\n[[File:WSSF File Photo3.jpg|thumb|World Ski and Snowboard Festival iTunes Concert Series]]\nThe '''World Ski & Snowboard Festival''' (WSSF) is an annual celebration of snowsports, music, arts and mountain culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=WSSF Official Website Media Page}}</ref> The Festival is held each April in [[Whistler, British Columbia|Whistler, British Columbia, Canada]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/place/Whistler,+BC/data=!4m2!3m1!1s0x54873cb203957b87:0x4ab741e875f5cff6?ved=2ahUKEwi0nOOk_5rfAhWohFQKHRjnAtEQ8gEwAHoECAAQAQ|title=Whistler|website=Whistler|language=en|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> and has been recognized as the largest annual winter sports and music festival in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> It has been called the snowsport industry's version of Burning Man.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wssf.com/urlRewrite.cfm?q=wssf-facts-stats|title=Article: Ski Magazine}}</ref>\n\nThe World Ski & Snowboard Festival was created by [http://www.dougperry.ca Doug Perry] in 1996.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> The festival was developed in a partnership between Perry, Tourism Whistler and Whistler/Blackcomb. \n\nThe inaugural WSSF in 1996 consisted of 22 sports events and competitions. In subsequent years it underwent exponential growth in attendance and media coverage,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/last-of-the-perry-brothers/Content?oid=2154331&storyPage=2|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine}}</ref> resulting in Whistler becoming the busiest mountain resort in North America in the month of April. At its peak, annual attendance reached an estimated 250,000 resort visits<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://archive.news.gov.bc.ca/releases/news_releases_2013-2017/2015jtst0045-000433.pdf|title=Gov.BC.ca News Archives}}</ref>and was televised in 122 countries.\n\nAn Economic Impact Assessment<ref>Canadian Sport Tourism Alliance</ref> conducted during the 2006 event found that the WSSF generated $37.7 million in economic activity for the province of British Columbia, with visitor spending and operational expenditure injecting more than $15.7 million into the Whistler economy. Over 28,000 hotel room nights were sold during the Festival, with 86% being directly attributed to WSSF.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://wssf.com/urlRewrite.cfm?q=wssf-facts-stats|title=Canadian Sport Tourism Alliance}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006 the ownership of the festival was consolidated in a joint acquisition of Perry's ownership stake by [https://www.whistler.com Tourism Whistler] and [https://www.whistlerblackcomb.com Whistler/Blackcomb].\n\nThe predecessor to WSSF was the World Technical Skiing Championships (WTSC).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> WTSC was created by [https://sites.google.com/d/1YBUBujka_cRbJd84ygLb7It7lRDBhZs2/p/14I-0LUxNreYAa5CbCfPiUVT4twC8NIwv/edit Doug Perry] as the world's first international freeskiing competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/we-are-whistler/Content?oid=2644306|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine \"20 years of WSSF\"}}</ref> The first event was staged on Blackcomb Mountain in April 1994 and was televised on ESPN in the United States and its international affiliates. WTSC was designed as a made-for-tv invitational event in which world champions, Olympians and skiing legends from the sport's major disciplines vied for the title of ''world's best all-mountain skier'' in a decathlon-format competition of freeskiing, GS racing, moguls and steeps down the Saudan Couloir. WTSC was modelled after Japan's largest skiing event, the All Japan Technical Skiing Championships, in which [http://www.dougperry.ca/photo1 Perry competed as a member of Team Salomon].\n\nThe inaugural World Technical Skiing Championships was groundbreaking in that it drew over 100 media outlets<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/festival-feedback/Content?oid=2140533|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine}}</ref> to Whistler at a time when the resort was just beginning to emerge as an international destination. The media attention seeded the idea of developing a more diverse annual event with the potential to attract more top athletes, media and attendees to Whistler Resort.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/festival-feedback/Content?oid=2140533|title=Article: Pique Newsmagazine}}</ref>\n\nThe 1996 World Ski & Snowboard Festival included the 2nd World Technical Skiing Championships, World Masters Alpine Open, Westbeach Snowboard Classic, Whistler Cup, Couloir Extreme Race and a ski industry symposium.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wssf.com/media/|title=Media \u2013 World Ski & Snowboard Festival|language=en-US|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref> Subsequent festivals expanded to include the Whistler Concert Series, World Skiing Invitational, World Snowboarding Invitational, World Snowboarding Championship, Kokanee Boardercross, Salomon Skiercross, Pro Photographer Showdown, Filmmaker Showdown, Brave Art, State of the Art, Fashion Exposed, Multiplicity, Intersection and many others.\n\nThe World Ski & Snowboard Festival has included Canada's largest free outdoor concert series<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.topeventscanada.com/BC-top-events-festivals-TELUS-World-Ski-Snowboard-Festival.html|title=Top Events Canada}}</ref> with 50 live acts per festival. Acts on the WSSF stage have included The Black Eyed Peas, Justin Timberlake, Nickelback, Michael Franti, Nas, Toots and the Maytals, and others.\n\nFrom 2001 through 2006, the World Ski & Snowboard was televised as a four-part series on the Global Television Network and was syndicated to 122 countries.\n\nIn 2018, the World Ski & Snowboard Festival was acquired in full by Vail Resorts, Inc. upon its acquisition of Whistler Blackcomb. Vail Resorts announced WSSF would continue under new management, Crankworx Events Inc., in a shorter 6-day format, running April 10\u201315, 2018. Tourism Whistler relinquished its 22-year part ownership of the property. 2018 also marked the return of the Saudan Couloir Ski Race Extreme after a 20-year hiatus.<ref>Vancouver Courier</ref> In 2019, Vail Resorts, owner of Whistler Blackcomb, announced the World Ski & Snowboard Festival would be shortened to 5 days, running April 10-14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/world-ski-and-snowboard-festival-founder-critical-of-new-direction-of-event/Content?oid=12456969|title=World Ski and Snowboard Festival founder critical of new direction of event|last=Barrett|first=Brandon|website=Pique|language=en|access-date=2019-01-15}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, the World Ski & Snowboard was acquired in full by [[Www.gibbonswhistler.com|Gibbons Whistler]] from Whistler Blackcomb.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.piquenewsmagazine.com/whistler/gibbons-whistler-buys-world-ski-and-snowboard-festival/Content?oid=14711060|title=Whistler Gibbons buys WSSF|last=|first=|date=|work=Pique Newsmagazine|access-date=}}</ref>The 2020 Festival was cancelled due to COVID-19 and the 25th Anniversary festival is scheduled for 2021.\n\n<br />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wssf.com World Ski and Snowboard Festival]\n\n[[Category:Snowboarding]]\n[[Category:Annual events in Canada]]\n[[Category:Whistler, British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Arts festivals in Canada]]\n[[Category:Music festivals in British Columbia]]\n[[Category:Art festivals in Canada]]\n", "name_user": "WhistlerJournal2", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/World_Ski_and_Snowboard_Festival"}
